aa(lp31
VWe made a guess. The guess was that schools in remote areas
p32
aVdo not have good enough teachers.
p33
aVIf they do have, they cannot retain those teachers.
p34
aVThey do not have good enough infrastructure.
p35
aVAnd if they had some infrastructure,
p36
aVthey have difficulty maintaining it.
p37
aVBut I wanted to check if this is true. So what I did last year was
p38
aVwe hired a car, looked up on Google,
p39
aVfound a route into northern India from New Delhi
p40
aVwhich, you know, which did not cross any big cities
p41
aVor any big metropolitan centers. Drove out about 300 kilometers,
p42
aVand wherever we found a school, administered a set of standard tests,
p43
aVand then took those test results and plotted them on a graph.
p44
aVThe graph was interesting, although you need to consider it carefully.
p45
aVI mean, this is a very small sample; you should not generalize from it.
p46
aVBut it was quite obvious, quite clear,
p47
aVthat for this particular route that I had taken,
p48
aVthe remoter the school was, the worse its results seemed to be.
p49
aVThat seemed a little damning,
p50
aVand I tried to correlate it with things like infrastructure,
p51
aVor with the availability of electricity, and things like that.
p52
aa(lp53
VTo my surprise, it did not correlate.
p54
aVIt did not correlate with the size of classrooms.
p55
aVIt did not correlate with the quality of the infrastructure.
p56
aVIt did not correlate with the poverty levels. It did not correlate.
p57
aVBut what happened was that when I administered a questionnaire
p58
aVto each of these schools, with one single question for the teachers \u2014 which was,
p59
aV"Would you like to move to an urban, metropolitan area?" \u2014
p60
aV69 percent of them said yes. And as you can see from that,
p61
aVthey say yes just a little bit out of Delhi,
p62
aVand they say no when you hit the rich suburbs of Delhi \u2014
p63
aVbecause, you know, those are relatively better off areas \u2014
p64
aVand then from 200 kilometers out of Delhi, the answer is consistently yes.
p65
aVI would imagine that a teacher who comes or walks into class
p66
aVevery day thinking that, I wish I was in some other school,
p67
aVprobably has a deep impact on what happens to the results.
p68
aVSo it looked as though teacher motivation and teacher migration
p69
aVwas a powerfully correlated thing with what was happening in primary schools,
p70
aVas opposed to whether the children have enough to eat,
p71
aVand whether they are packed tightly into classrooms
p72
aVand that sort of thing. It appears that way.
