aa(lp74
VWhen you take education and technology, then I find in the literature that,
p75
aVyou know, things like websites, collaborative environments \u2014
p76
aVyou've been listening to all that in the morning \u2014
p77
aVit's always piloted first in the best schools, the best urban schools,
p78
aVand, according to me, biases the result.
p79
aVThe literature \u2014 one part of it, the scientific literature \u2014
p80
aVconsistently blames ET as being over-hyped and under-performing.
p81
aVThe teachers always say, well, it's fine, but it's too expensive for what it does.
p82
aVBecause it's being piloted in a school where the students are already getting,
p83
aVlet's say, 80 percent of whatever they could do.
p84
aVYou put in this new super-duper technology, and now they get 83 percent.
p85
aVSo the principal looks at it and says,
p86
aV3 percent for 300,000 dollars? Forget it.
p87
aVIf you took the same technology and piloted it into one of those remote schools,
p88
aVwhere the score was 30 percent, and, let's say, took that up to 40 percent \u2014
p89
aVthat will be a completely different thing.
p90
aVSo the relative change that ET, Educational Technology, would make,
p91
aVwould be far greater at the bottom of the pyramid than at the top,
p92
aVbut we seem to be doing it the other way about.
